<DOC><DOCNO> AP900416-0004 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-16-90 2352EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-BoxOffice     04-16 0408</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Box Office,0425</SECOND><HEAD>`Ninja Turtles' Banks Another $14.1 Million</HEAD><BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE><BYLINE>AP Entertainment Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   ``Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles'' was No. 1 atthe box office for the third straight week, becoming thehighest-grossing independent film in U.S. history.   ``Ninja Turtles,'' released by New Line Cinema, took in $73million in its first three weeks, including $14.11 million lastweek, according to figures Monday from Exhibitor Relations Co.   Disney's ``Pretty Woman,'' a Pygmalion tale starring RichardGere as a powerful businessman and Julia Roberts as a streetwalker,was second with $10.1 million.   ``Ninja Turtles'' overtook Vestron's 1987 ``Dirty Dancing,''which held the record for biggest North American box-office take byan independently produced movie at $63 million.   Otherwise, box-office business over the weekend was just fair.   ``The Easter egg hunts cut into the kids a little bit,'' saidJohn Krier of Exhibitor Relations.   In third place was the Tom Clancy techno-thriller ``The Hunt forRed October,'' with ticket sales of $4.26 million. ``Ernest Goes toJail,'' the latest installment in the adventures of an obnoxiousbumpkin, was fourth with $4.25 million.   Here are the top movie ticket sales for Friday through Sunday astallied by Exhibitor Relations, with distributor, weekend gross,number of theater screens, average per screen, total gross andnumber of weeks in release.   Figures are based on a combination of actual box-office receiptsand studio projections where actual figures are not immediatelyavailable.   1. ``Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles,'' New Line, $14.1 million,2,377 screens, $5,917 per screen, $72.9 million, three weeks.   2. ``Pretty Woman,'' Disney, $10.1 million, 1,707 screens,$5,927 per screen, $59.3 million, four weeks.   3. ``The Hunt for Red October,'' Paramount, $4.26 million, 1,702screens, $2,503 per screen, $89.8 million, seven weeks.   4. ``Ernest Goes to Jail,'' Disney, $4.25 million, 1,956screens, $2,172 per screen, $12.6 million, two weeks.   5. ``The First Power,'' Orion, $3.8 million, 1,336 screens,$2,858 per screen, $11.7 million, two weeks.   6. ``Crazy People,'' Paramount, $3.4 million, 1,389 screens,$2,417 per screen, $4.2 million, one week.   7. ``I Love You to Death,'' Tri-Star, $2.7 million, 1,095screens, $2,425 per screen, $8 million, two week.   8. ``Driving Miss Daisy,'' Warner Bros., $2.2 million, 1,387screens, $1,617 per screen, $90.4 million, 18 weeks.   9. ``Cry Baby,'' Universal, $1.6 million, 1,236 screens, $1,255per screen, $5.5 million, two weeks.   10. ``The Gods Must Be Crazy II,'' Weintraub, $1.2 million, 321screens, $3,676 per screen, $1.2 million, one week.</TEXT></DOC>